<worksheet xml:id="activity-tutorial-11">
  <title>Tutorial-11</title>
  <introduction>
                <p>
                    Following exercises are taken from Section 14.4 of the book <em>Abstract Algebra</em> by Dummit and Foote.
                </p>
  </introduction>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Determine the Galois closure of <m>\Q\left(\sqrt{1+\sqrt{2}}\right)</m> over <m>\Q</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Find a primitive generator for <m>\Q\left(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3},\sqrt{5}\right)/\Q</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>F</m> be a field contained in <m>M_n(\Q)</m>. Show that <m>[F:\Q]\leq n</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            For any Galois extension <m>K/F</m>, show that the irreducible polynomial <m>f(x)\in F[x]</m> factors in <m>K[x]</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>p</m> be a prime number and <m>F</m> a field. Let <m>K/F</m> be a Galois extension whose Galois group is a <m>p</m>-group.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Let <m>L/K</m> be a <m>p</m>-extension. Show that the Galois closure of <m>L/F</m> is a <m>p</m>-extension of <m>F</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Give an example to show that the above result need not be true if <m>K/F</m> is not Galois even if <m>[K:F]</m> is a power of <m>p</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>